# Chess Engine Rust

[![MIT License](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-MIT-blue.svg)](LICENSE.md)
[![Rust](https://img.shields.io/badge/rust-1.75%2B-orange.svg)](https://www.rust-lang.org/)
[![Platform](https://img.shields.io/badge/platform-cross--platform-green.svg)](#platform-support)

A chess engine implemented in Rust with support for standard chess rules and FEN parsing. The engine provides a simple API for move generation, position evaluation, and game management.

**Use cases**: Game development, chess analysis tools, educational projects.

---

## Quick Start

### Installation

```bash
# Add to your Cargo.toml
[dependencies]
chess-engine = { path = "crates/chess-engine" }
chess-core = { path = "crates/chess-core" }
```

### Basic Usage

```rust
use chess_engine::{ChessEngineBuilder, Color};

fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    // Create engine
    let mut engine = ChessEngineBuilder::new()
        .with_depth(6)
        .build()?;

    // Make moves
    engine.make_move_from_uci("e2e4")?;  // 1. e4
    engine.make_move_from_uci("e7e5")?;  // 1... e5

    // Get engine's move
    if let Some(best_move) = engine.find_best_move()? {
        println!("Engine plays: {}", best_move);
        println!("Evaluation: {}", engine.evaluate());
    }

    Ok(())
}
```

## Features

### Core Functionality
- Standard chess rules implementation
- FEN position parsing and export
- Legal move generation
- Position evaluation
- Basic search algorithms

### Architecture
- Multi-crate design with clean separation
- Comprehensive test coverage (115+ tests)
- Cross-platform compilation support
- FFI bindings for C and Java integration

### Technical Details
- Bitboard-based board representation
- Alpha-beta search with basic optimizations
- Material and positional evaluation
- Support for standard chess formats

